records.nl_statement: Let $N$ be a positive integer. Let $M$ be an integer relatively prime to $N$ and let $d$ be an integer relatively prime to $\varphi(N)$, where $\varphi$ denotes Euler's $\varphi$-function. Prove that if $M_{1} \equiv M^{d} \pmod N$ then $M \equiv M_{1}^{d^{\prime}} \pmod N$ where $d^{\prime}$ is the inverse of $d \bmod \varphi(N)$: $d d^{\prime} \equiv 1 \pmod {\varphi(N)}$.
